tekken-coach
============

This product includes frame-data derived from third-party community sources. The data is
used with attribution; no third-party application *code* is vendored (see THIRD_PARTY_LICENSES
for the code/data split).

Frame data (assets/framedata/)
------------------------------
Frame-data snapshots under `assets/framedata/` are ingested (via `fetch-framedata`) from the
Wavu-derived CSV files published by the `pbruvoll/tekkendocs` repository, which is the source
behind tekkendocs.com. The underlying frame data originates from the Tekken community, notably:

  - tekkendocs.com
  - rbnorway.org

Each snapshot's `manifest.json` records the exact pinned upstream commit SHA and per-character
source checksums, so every snapshot is reproducible and traceable to its source.

The `pbruvoll/tekkendocs` *application code* is restrictively licensed and is NOT used or
vendored here — only the published *data* is ingested, with the attribution above. See docs/05
§3.1 for the data-vs-code licensing split.

Memory reader (src/tekken_coach/reader/, assets/offsets/)
---------------------------------------------------------
The read-only Tekken 8 memory reader is an original implementation informed by the memory-layout
knowledge of the MIT-licensed TekkenBot root (WAZAAAAA0/TekkenBot, (c) 2017 roguelike2d). That
project is credited for the layout knowledge; its MIT copyright/permission text is retained in
THIRD_PARTY_LICENSES (MIT is irrevocable for the code it covered).

  - Offsets, addresses, and AOB signatures are FACTS/DATA, not code: they live under
    `assets/offsets/` as versioned tables, never hard-coded in source.
  - The within-struct field-offset map and pointer-chain shape seeded into
    `assets/offsets/probe-manifest.json` (`base_scan`, `global_scan`) are FACTS/DATA taken from the
    community-known Tekken 8 layout as recorded in the dcep93 fork's committed `memory_address.ini`
    data file — NOT from its `update_memory_address.py` script, which was not read, copied, or
    paraphrased. This includes the encoded state-word offsets (`state_fields`) and the global/match
    struct's chain shape and field offsets. The global field offsets are seeded UNASSIGNED (we take
    the addresses as facts; which one is the frame counter is re-derived by behavior).
  - `assets/offsets/state-map.json` — the encoded state VALUE -> meaning map — contains NO
    fork-derived values. It ships as an empty, uncalibrated skeleton and is filled in by first-party
    observation of the running game (the protocol in docs/02 §8). The fork's enum values were not
    read or used, even though docs/02 §5 rule 1 would arguably permit them as facts.
  - The `update-offsets` re-discovery command (C4c/C4d/C4e, src/tekken_coach/reader/discovery/) is a
    CLEAN-ROOM re-implementation of the Jin-vs-Kazuya practice-mode technique (open Jin vs Kazuya,
    scan to re-derive addresses — an unprotected idea): the C4c heap value-scan, the C4d
    code-signature / pointer-chain base derivation, and the C4e global-anchor and transform-component
    scans (candidate-generate-and-validate with the field layout, or observed behavior, as the
    oracle) are all original; none reads, copies, or paraphrases the fork's
    `update_memory_address.py`.
  - The reader is READ-ONLY by construction: no memory-write or input-injection primitive exists
    anywhere in the package (the bot/input half of the ancestral TekkenBot is not ported).

See docs/02 §5 and THIRD_PARTY_LICENSES for the full data-vs-code split and licensing posture.

Punisher profiles (assets/punishers/)
--------------------------------------
The curated per-character punisher profiles under `assets/punishers/` are frame-number facts
(startup, notation, launch property) hand-curated for the scoped matchups. Specific block-punish
recommendations are cross-checked against the same community sources plus:

  - okizeme.gg
  - wavu.wiki

These are numeric facts, not vendored code. See docs/05 §3.1 / §4.1 for the sourcing posture.
